@node SHAREWARE "ARCHandler: Shareware Notice"
@prev DISCLAIMER
@next INTRODUCTION

  @{b}@{u}ARCHandler is Shareware@{ub}@{uu}

This package is released as shareware. This means you can copy it freely as
long  as  you  don't ask any money for it, except perhaps a nominal fee for
copying.  If  you use this package on a regular base, you should send @{"me" link AUTHOR} a
contribution of 500 BEF or USD 20. Send money by International Money Order,
EuroCheck (in BEF!) or Cash.

When   you   send  your  registration  fee  you  will  be  send  a  written
acknowledgment  including your personal key file. This file is your private
key file, you are not allowed to copy it, except for backup purposes.

If you can be reached via EMail (or FIDO) please include your address, this
makes it easier (and quicker?) to send you your keyfile.

Magazines that want to include @{b}ARCHandler@{ub} on their coverdisk(s) should also
register  @{b}ARCHandler@{ub}  (one  registration fee) and send one free copy of the
magazine (including disks) to the @{"author" link AUTHOR}.

The  package  is  Copyright  © Rafael D'Halleweyn, All Rights Reserved. The
author  reserves the right to change the status of this package whenever he
finds it appropriate.

This  package  should  not  be  spread  in  any  other form than an LhA (or
equivalent)  archive  and  all  parts  of it should be spread together. The
package  may  not  be  altered in any way and cannot be used for commercial
purposes  without  the  prior written permission of the author.

Distribution  of  the program on any medium (CD, floppy, ...) in such a way
that  it is ready to be used (eg. as a front-end for a CD-ROM) requires the
permission of the @{"author" link AUTHOR}.

The   installation-script  (`Install')  and  the  extra  commands  it  uses
(`FindCommand',  `PrefLanguage'  and  `StartARC')  are also copyrighted and
can't  be  used  in  any  other  project/archive  without the prior written
permission of the author.
@endnode
@node INTRODUCTION "ARCHandler: Introduction"
@prev SHAREWARE
@next REQUIREMENTS

  @{b}@{u}Introduction to ARCHandler@{ub}@{uu}

@{"Archives" link ARCHIVE}  (such  as  @{"LhA" link LHA}  , Zip, Zoo, Tar, ...) are very easy to store and
move  large  amounts  of  files.  However,  if  you  wish  to use the files
contained  in  the  archive  you  always  have  to extract the files first.
Secondly,  to  easily  browse  through the archive, you have to extract the
whole archive.

Wouldn't  it  be  easier if you could treat archives just like directories:
move to a directory, look which files are in the directory and possibly use
one of those files.

I have already heard a lot of suggestions in this direction, so the idea is
neither  mine nor is it original. But I've never seen an implementation, so
I tried to make my own and this is the result.

Currently the @{b}ARCHandler@{ub} only supports @{"lha" link LHA}-archives.

Remember @{b}ARCHandler@{ub} is shareware.
@endnode
@node ARCHIVE "ARCHandler: What is an archive?"
@prev ARCHIVE
@next ARCHIVE

In  this  text the word @{i}archive @{ui}is used to indicated a group of files, that
are  stored in one big file, possibly also containing the file-structure of
the original (directories) and maybe using compression to store the files.

@{i}Archives @{ui}are mainly used to move large amounts of data from one computer to
another  (via  disk/modem/ftp/...).  @{i}Archives @{ui}are also an easy way to store
that data.

@{b}ARCHandler@{ub} currently only supports @{"lha" link LHA}-archives.
@endnode
@node LHA "ARCHandler: What is an lha-archive?"
@prev LHA
@next LHA

LhA  is  probably  the  most  widely  used archiver on the Amiga. It uses a
Lempel-Ziv  sliding-window  (LZ77)  together with dynamic or static Huffman
coding  (LZH)  the  size  of  the  files  in  the  @{"archive" link ARCHIVE}.  Several other
LZH-archives  exist  for  the  Amiga (LhArcA, LhArc, LZ, LhEx, ...) and for
UNIX, MS-DOS, Macintosh and Atari machines.
@endnode
@node REQUIREMENTS "ARCHandler: Requirements"
@prev INTRODUCTION
@next STARTING

  @{b}@{u}Requirements to use ARCHandler@{ub}@{uu}

@{b}ARCHandler@{ub}  currently requires an Amiga running Workbench/Kickstart 2.04 or
higher, it also needs the following libraries (they should be in your LIBS:
directory):  `asl.library' and `commodities.library'. The program will also
use  the  `locale.library'  when it is available (Workbench 2.1 and up). To
use the @{"online-help" link HELP} you also need the `amigaguide.library'.

To  extract  files  from @{"lha-archive" link LHA}, @{b}ARCHandler@{ub} uses the 'LhA' command (©
Stefan Boberg), both the registered and evaluation version should work.

To test the handler, a few lha-archives can also be very handy :).
@endnode
@node STARTING "ARCHandler: Starting"
@prev REQUIREMENTS
@next USING

  @{b}@{u}Starting ARCHandler@{ub}@{uu}

You  can place @{b}ARCHandler@{ub} anywhere you want, but if you change the position
of  the  program, you should always check if it is still able to access the
@{"FILESDIR" link FILESDIR_ARG}-directory   (if   you  installed  @{b}ARCHandler@{ub}  with  the  included
installation script this should be no problem).

@{b}ARCHandler@{ub}  can  be started from the Workbench or from a Shell. You can use
different @{"arguments" link ARGUMENTS} to change the settings of @{b}ARCHandler@{ub}.

If you want to start @{b}ARCHandler@{ub} on every boot-up of your computer you could
place the program in the 'WbStartup' drawer of your startup-partition.
@endnode
@node USING "ARCHandler: Using"
@next ARGUMENTS
@prev STARTING

  @{b}@{u}Using ARCHandler@{ub}@{uu}

@{b}ARCHandler@{ub} manifests itself in three different ways:
  @{"the filesystem              " link FILESYSTEM} (access files and archives)
  @{"the graphical user interface" link GUI} (change the settings)
  @{"the commodity               " link COMMODITY} (pop up user interface, flush archives)
@endnode
@node FILESYSTEM "ARCHandler: FileSystem"
@prev FILESYSTEM
@next GUI
@toc USING

  @{b}The ARCHandler FileSystem@{ub}

You  should  be  able  to use the filesystem (volume and DOS-device) as any
other   Amiga-filesystem  (like  the  one  on  your  floppy/harddisk).  The
root-directory  of  the  filesystems  contains  all the volumes that can be
accessed at that time. When you enter one of these volumes you will see all
the  normal files that are on that volume.

The  big  difference  with the original filesystem is that all the archives
are  now represented as directories (they can even have there own icon, see
@{"Workbench support" link WORKBENCH}). Inside these archive-directories you will find all the
files  that  are in the archive (the may be placed in subdirectories of the
archive-directory).

All  the  files (real and those in the archives) and directories (real, the
volumes and the archives) on the filesystem can be used as normal files and
directories.

The @{b}ARCHandler@{ub} filesystem has two parts: the DOS-device and the volume. The
DOS-device  (this  just  like  `DF0:') can be used to access the filesystem
from filerequester, directory utilities. The volume (like a disk `Stuff' in
the device `DF0:') can be used to access the filesystem from the Workbench.

Since  version 2.0a it is also possible to access volumes through the names
of  devices  or assigns. These names are always expanded to the volume name
(and  path  for assigns). Device and assigns are not visible in the root of
the  filesystem. For example `CD ARC:DF0' will change the current directory
to `Archives:Disk_in_drive_0', or `List ARC:C' gives the directory contents
of `Archives:Workbench/C'.

Please note that small changes in an archive (e.g.  renaming  a  directory)
can take a @{i}very @{ui}long time: be patient.

Some actions may work a little different:
  @{" Delete  " link ACTION_DELETE_OBJECT}
  @{" MakeDir " link ACTION_CREATE_DIR}
  @{" Rename  " link ACTION_RENAME_OBJECT}
@endnode
@node ACTION_DELETE_OBJECT "ARCHandler: Delete"
@prev ACTION_DELETE_OBJECT
@next ACTION_CREATE_DIR

  ACTION_DELETE_OBJECT, Delete

When  you delete the last file in a directory of an archive, it is possible
that  the archive no longer contains a reference to the directory. The next
time that you use the archive this directory will be gone.

If  you want to delete an entire archive it is better to delete the archive
on  the  normal  volume. If you use @{b}ARCHandler@{ub} to delete it, it will take a
lot  of  time: first all the files in the archive will be deleted and after
that  the archive  itself will be deleted.  If you really want to delete an
archive through @{b}ARCHandler@{ub} you should be @{i}very @{ui}patient.
@endnode
@node ACTION_CREATE_DIR "ARCHandler: MakeDir"
@prev ACTION_DELETE_OBJECT
@next ACTION_RENAME_OBJECT

  ACTION_CREATE_DIR, MakeDir

You  can  use  MakeDir  to create new archives. @{b}ARCHandler@{ub} decides if a new
directory  will  become  a  new  archive by looking at the directory's name
(even if the @{"Archive Recognition" link RECOGNITION_GAD} cycle gadget is set to `File Contents').
@endnode
@node ACTION_RENAME_OBJECT "ARCHandler: Rename"
@prev ACTION_CREATE_DIR
@next ACTION_RENAME_OBJECT

  ACTION_RENAME_OBJECT, Rename

Renaming a directory in an archive can take a lot of time: if the directory
contains  a  lot  of files and/or subdirectories, the name of the directory
will  have  to be changed for each of these files/directories. Every change
may  alter  the  size  of  the archive, if this happens a large part of the
archive has to be moved (this may happen for every file/directory).

When  you  move  the  last  file  in  a  directory of an archive to another
directory,  it  is possible that the archive no longer contains a reference
to  the  directory.  The  next time that you use the archive this directory
will be gone.
@endnode
@node GUI "ARCHandler: Graphical User Interface"
@prev FILESYSTEM
@next COMMODITY
@toc USING

  @{b}The ARCHandler Graphical User Interface@{ub}

@{b}ARCHandler@{ub}  has a graphical user interface (with standard GadTools gadgets)
that  allows  you  to  change the @{b}ARCHandler@{ub} settings. All the windows (and
gadgets)  that  the  program  opens  are  font  and  locale  sensitive. The
@{b}ARCHandler@{ub}  User  Interface  tries  to  stick as closely as possible to the
`Amiga User Interface Style Guide'.

The  user interface contains multiple windows and requesters. The different
windows  never block each other, it is not because another window is opened
that  the  previous  window can no longer be used (they are non-modal). The
requesters that pop up when you use one of the popup-gadgets (these gadgets
have  the imagery of an arrow pointing down), do block the window that they
originated from.

All  the  windows  have @{"context sensitive help" link HELP}: position the pointer above
the  window  or  gadget  and  press the `Help' key. When a string-gadget is
active,  you  can  get  help  on  the  attribute you're editing by pressing
`Help'.  You  can also receive help by pressing `Help' when a button-gadget
is  depressed  (this  also  works when the gadget is depressed by using the
buttons  shortcut). Menus also have context sensitive help, select the menu
item  you  want  more  information about, but don't release the right mouse
button, now press help.

The  user  interface  is  fully keyboard controlable. The shortcuts for the
gadgets  appear  in  the  text  of  the  gadget,  the underscored character
represents  the  shortcut-key.  The  gadget  that  has an extra dark border
around  its  button  can also be activated with the `Return' key. The `Esc'
key is always a safe way out.

When  the  the underscored character is a diacretic character or some other
character  that  has  to  be  generated  with  multiple  key presses and/or
multiple  qualifiers  (like Shift, Ctrl, Alt), you should only use the last
key  and  you  don't  need  to use the qualifiers. For example, on a french
keyboard,  the  gadget  `_Élčve' can be accessed with the `é'/`2' key; on a
usa keyboard you would have to press `e'.

All  gadgets  react  immediatly  when they are activated with the keyboard,
except  for  the button gadgets. The button gadgets will change there state
to indicate that they are selected, the gadget will only react when the key
is  released. You can cancel the button gadget when it is already selected,
by pressing an (extra) qualifier.

The  user  interface also uses popup-gadgets. When you press one of these a
requester  will  appear,  that  request  some  information  from you. These
popup-gadgets  don't  have there own shortcut-key, but you can select these
gadgets  by pressing the shortcut-key of the gadget that they are connected
to plus the `Control' or `Ctrl' key.

Some  windows contain slider gadgets (they allow you to choose a value in a
given  range).  The  normal  shortcut-key  of these gadgets adds one to the
value  of the gadget. When you use the same key together with a `Shift' key
the value will decrease.

Cycle  gadgets  allow  you to choose one from several options. You can also
`cycle'  through  the  different options by using the gadgets shortcut-key.
Together  with  the `Shift' key the gadget will cycle backwards through its
options.

Currently  @{b}ARCHandler@{ub}  can  be  used  in  Dansk (Danish), Deutsch (German),
English,  Espańol (Spanish), Français (French), Italiano (Italian), Svenska
(Swedish), Suomi (Finnish), Portuguęs (Portuguese) and Nederlands (Dutch).
@endnode
@node COMMODITY "ARCHandler: Commodity"
@prev GUI
@next COMMODITY
@toc USING

  @{b}The ARCHandler Commodity@{ub}

The   @{b}ARCHandler@{ub}   Commodity   Interface   can   be  used  to  pop  up  the
@{"graphical user interface" link GUI}, with the `Exchange' program or with the @{"Hot Key" link HOTKEY_GAD}.

You  can also use the `Exchange' program to quit the program (note that the
program may not always be able to quit).

The commodity interface can also be used to flush all unused @{"archive-lists" link FILELISTS}
from memory.

You should also note that @{b}ARCHandler@{ub} can not be made inactive: changing the
`Active'/`Inactive'  state of @{b}ARCHandler@{ub} with the `Exchange' program has no
effect.  But  when  @{b}ARCHandler@{ub}  is  trying  to  quit it will inactivate its
commodity.  At  that  point  @{b}ARCHandler@{ub}  can be reactivated by pressing the
hotkey (@{"CX_POPKEY" link CX_POPUP_ARG}, @{"HOTKEY" link HOTKEY_GAD}) or by activating the commodity.
@endnode
@node ARGUMENTS "ARCHandler: Arguments"
@prev USING
@next WINDOWS

  @{b}@{u}Arguments@{ub}@{uu}

When  @{b}ARCHandler@{ub}  is started you can specify the settings of the program by
specifying some arguments. @{b}ARCHandler@{ub} will always try to read the tooltypes
in the program's icon (even when started from a Shell). When @{b}ARCHandler@{ub} was
started  from  a  Shell  it will also read the specified arguments from the
commandline  (with  ReadArgs()),  overriding the arguments specified in the
icon.

@{b}ARCHandler@{ub} recognizes the following arguments:
  @{"CX_POPUP     " link CX_POPUP_ARG}
  @{"CX_POPKEY    " link CX_POPKEY_ARG}
  @{"CX_PRIORITY  " link CX_PRIORITY_ARG}
  @{"FLUSHKEY     " link FLUSHKEY_ARG}
  @{"DEVICENAME   " link DEVICENAME_ARG}
  @{"VOLUMENAME   " link VOLUMENAME_ARG}
  @{"PRIORITY     " link PRIORITY_ARG}
  @{"SCANDELAY    " link SCANDELAY_ARG}
  @{"FILESDIR     " link FILESDIR_ARG}
  @{"RECOGNITION  " link RECOGNITION_ARG}
  @{"TEMPDIR      " link TEMPDIR_ARG}
  @{"BUFFERS      " link BUFFERS_ARG}
  @{"KEEPTIME     " link KEEPTIME_ARG}
  @{"LHACOMMAND   " link LHACOMMAND_ARG}
  @{"IGNOREVOLUMES" link IGNOREVOLUMES_ARG}

obsolete:
  @{"ONLYEXTENSION" link ONLYEXTENSION_ARG}


When  you  use  @{b}ARCHandler@{ub}  from the Workbench, you can change or add these
arguments  by  changing or adding the Tool Type (with the same name) in the
window that appears when you select the `Information...' menu item.

When  you  use @{b}ARCHandler@{ub} from a Shell you can also use the Tool Types. But
the  arguments  you  specify on the commandline overwrite the values in the
tooltypes. @{b}ARCHandler@{ub} uses this template:

  CX_POPUP/K,CX_POPKEY/K,CX_PRIORITY/K/N,FLUSHKEY/K,DEVICENAME=DEV/K,
  VOLUMENAME=VOL/K,PRIORITY/K/N,SCANDELAY/K/N,FILESDIR/K,
  RECOGNITION=RECOG/K/N,TEMPDIR/K,BUFFERS/K/N,KEEPTIME/K/N,
  LHACOMMAND=LHA/K,IGNOREVOLUMES/K,ONLYEXTENSION=ONLYEXT/S

@{b}ARCHandler@{ub}  tries  to save its settings in the program's icon as Tool Types
(even   when  started  from  a  Shell).  The  icon  is  thus  used  as  the
configuration file.
@endnode
@node CX_POPUP_ARG "ARCHandler: CX_POPUP argument"
@prev CX_POPUP_ARG
@next CX_POPKEY_ARG
@toc ARGUMENTS

  @{b}CX_POPUP@{ub}

With  CX_POPUP  you  can  choose if @{b}ARCHandler@{ub} will pop up its @{"Main Window" link MAINWINDOW}
when  it  is  started. You should specify `YES' or `ON' if you do want this
window   to   be  opened.  Otherwise  you  have  to  use  `CX_POPUP=NO'  or
`CX_POPUP=OFF'.

This argument defaults to `YES'.

This   setting  can  also  be  changed  with  the  @{"Pop Up" link POPUP_GAD}  gadget  in  the
@{"Commodity Preferences" link CXPREFS} window.
@endnode
@node CX_POPKEY_ARG "ARCHandler: CX_POPKEY argument"
@prev CX_POPUP_ARG
@next CX_PRIORITY_ARG
@toc ARGUMENTS

  @{b}CX_POPKEY@{ub}

With  CX_POPKEY  you specify the key combination that can be used to pop up
@{b}ARCHandler's@{ub}  @{"Main Window" link MAINWINDOW}  when  the  program  is  already  running.  This
argument  should  be a standard Commodities key combination as described in
`Acceptable  Key  Combinations'  of the `Commodities Drawer' section of the
`Workbench  User's  Guide'.

When  you  specify  an  empty  string  for  this argument, @{b}ARCHandler@{ub} won't
generate a pop up key.

This  argument  defaults  to  `Ctrl  Alt a' on Workbench 2.1 and higher, on
Workbench 2.04 `Control Alt a' is used.

This  setting  can  also  be  changed  with  the  @{"Hot Key" link HOTKEY_GAD}  gadget  in  the
@{"Commodity Preferences" link CXPREFS} window.
@endnode
@node CX_PRIORITY_ARG "ARCHandler: CX_PRIORITY argument"
@prev CX_POPKEY_ARG
@next FLUSHKEY_ARG
@toc ARGUMENTS

  @{b}CX_PRIORITY@{ub}

With  CX_PRIORITY  you pick the priority of the @{b}ARCHandler@{ub} Commodity in the
chain  of  all  the  running  commodities. This argument should be a number
between -10 and 10.

This arguments defaults to 0.

This  setting  can  also  be  changed  with  the  @{"Priority" link CX_PRIORITY_GAD}  gadget  in the
@{"Commodity Preferences" link CXPREFS} window.
@endnode
@node FLUSHKEY_ARG "ARCHandler: FLUSHKEY argument"
@prev CX_PRIORITY_ARG
@next DEVICENAME_ARG
@toc ARGUMENTS

  @{b}FLUSHKEY@{ub}

With FLUSHKEY you specify the key combination that can be used to flush all
the  unused  @{"archive-file-lists" link FILELISTS}  from  memory.  This  argument should be a
standard  Commodities  key  combination  as  described  in  `Acceptable Key
Combinations'  of the `Commodities Drawer' section of the `Workbench User's
Guide'.

When you specify an empty string for this argument, @{b}ARCHandler@{ub} won't create
a flush key.

This  argument  defaults  to  `Ctrl  Alt f' on Workbench 2.1 and higher, on
Workbench 2.04 `Control Alt f' is used.

This  setting  can  also  be  changed  with  the  @{"Flush Key" link FLUSHKEY_GAD}  gadget  in  the
@{"Commodity Preferences" link CXPREFS} window.
@endnode
@node DEVICENAME_ARG "ARCHandler: DEVICENAME argument"
@prev FLUSHKEY_ARG
@next VOLUMENAME_ARG
@toc ARGUMENTS

  @{b}DEVICENAME@{ub}

The  DEVICENAME  argument can be used to specify the name of the @{b}ARCHandler@{ub}
@{"DOS-device" link FILESYSTEM}.  This  is the name that will appear in the `Unit' field of the
output  of  the `Info' command. This argument should be a string, without a
colon  (`:')! (You can compare this name with the name `DF0:' for the first
internal floppy drive.)

This argument defaults to `ARC'.

This  setting  can  also  be  changed  with  the @{"Device Name" link DEVNAME_GAD} gadget in the
@{"Device Preferences" link DEVPREFS} window.
@endnode
@node VOLUMENAME_ARG "ARCHandler: VOLUMENAME argument"
@prev DEVICENAME_ARG
@next PRIORITY_ARG
@toc ARGUMENTS

  @{b}VOLUMENAME@{ub}

With  the  VOLUMENAME  argument  you can choose the name for the @{b}ARCHandler@{ub}
@{"volume" link FILESYSTEM}.  This is the name that will appear in the Workbench. This argument
should  be a string, without a colon (`:')! (You can compare this name with
the name of a floppy `Stuff' inserted in any floppy drive.)

This argument defaults to `Archives'.

This  setting  can  also  be  changed  with  the @{"Volume Name" link VOLNAME_GAD} gadget in the
@{"Device Preferences" link DEVPREFS} window.
@endnode
@node PRIORITY_ARG "ARCHandler: PRIORITY argument"
@prev VOLUMENAME_ARG
@next SCANDELAY_ARG
@toc ARGUMENTS

  @{b}PRIORITY@{ub}

The  PRIORITY  argument  is  used to specify the priority of the @{b}ARCHandler@{ub}
process.  This process handles all the @{"filesystem" link FILESYSTEM} actions and also handles
the  @{"windows" link WINDOWS}.  This  argument  should  be  a number between -5 and +15. By
specifying  a  higher  number,  the  filesystem will have a @{i}relative @{ui}faster
response time on a @{i}busy system.@{ui}

Normally,  filesystems  have a higher priority then other processes because
other  processes  have to wait on these filesystems. This argument defaults
to 7.

Note that this argument does not change the extraction time of archives. To
extract archives, @{b}ARCHandler@{ub} generates a new process at priority zero.

This  setting  can  also  be  changed with the @{"Task Priority" link TASKPRI_GAD} gadget in the
@{"Device Preferences" link DEVPREFS} window.

Note  that  PRIORITY  and  @{"CX_PRIORITY" link CX_PRIORITY_ARG}  are  used  to change two @{i}different
@{ui}properties!
@endnode
@node SCANDELAY_ARG "ARCHandler: SCANDELAY argument"
@prev PRIORITY_ARG
@next FILESDIR_ARG
@toc ARGUMENTS

  @{b}SCANDELAY@{ub}

Because  the @{b}ARCHandler@{ub} @{"filesystem" link FILESYSTEM} has all the volumes in its root volume,
it  has  to  scan  the AmigaDOS list of volumes. Because new volumes can be
created  or  inserted,  or  the name of the current volumes can be changed,
this  scanning has to be repeated. Normally, when a new volume is inserted,
its  filesystem  will  generate a DISKINSERTED event (or DISKREMOVED when a
volume  is removed). @{b}ARCHandler@{ub} will also catch these events and then start
to scan the AmigaDOS volume list.

This argument should be a number between 1 and 9. This specifies the number
of seconds between each scan. This argument defaults to 4 seconds.

This  setting  can  also  be  changed  with  the  @{"Scan Delay" link SCANDELAY_GAD} gadget in the
@{"Device Preferences" link DEVPREFS} window.
@endnode
@node FILESDIR_ARG "ARCHandler: FILESDIR argument"
@prev SCANDELAY_ARG
@next RECOGNITION_ARG
@toc ARGUMENTS

  @{b}FILESDIR@{ub}

To  make  it easy to access files from the @{"Workbench" link WORKBENCH}, @{b}ARCHandler@{ub} adds some
extra  files  to  the  filesystem.  These  files are normally stored in the
directory  `PROGDIR:ARCFiles' (`PROGDIR:' is the directory where @{b}ARCHandler@{ub}
is placed). With this argument you can specify another directory.

All  the  files  that are placed in this directory can be accessed from the
root  of  the  filesystem. Only `Disk.info' and `.backdrop' will be visible
(when  you  examine  the  root  `List  ARC:').  You  can  use this to add a
`Node.rinfo' file, for the ParNET package.

By default @{b}ARCHandler@{ub} uses the `PROGDIR:ARCFiles' directory.

This  setting  can  also  be  changed  with  the @{"Extra Files" link EXTRAFILES_GAD} gadget in the
@{"Device Preferences" link DEVPREFS} window.
@endnode
@node RECOGNITION_ARG "ARCHandler: RECOGNITION argument"
@prev FILESDIR_ARG
@next TEMPDIR_ARG

  @{b}RECOGNITION@{ub}

With  the  RECOGNITION  argument you select the method that @{b}ARCHandler@{ub} will
use  to  recognize archives. This argument is a number between 0 and 2 with
the following meaning:

0: `Filename only'
    @{b}ARCHandler@{ub}  will  only  look  at  the name of the files to recognize an
    archive (eg. an @{"LhA-archives" link LHA} has a file-extension `.lha' or `.lzh').

    This  will  give the fastest access to directories. But it can make the
    wrong decision.

1: `Name and Contents'
    @{b}ARCHandler@{ub}  first  checks  the  name of file (like in `Filename only'),
    after that it opens the file to see if it is really an archive.

    This will always make the right decision (except corrupt archives), but
    it  takes  much  longer  to  scan  a directory: it will first check the
    filename and if that matches it will open the file.

2: `File Contents'
    @{b}ARCHandler@{ub}  will only look at the contents of a file to decide if it is
    an archive.

    The  file will always be opened (without looking at the filename). This
    allows  you  to  give any name to the archive. Since all the files in a
    directory have to be opened it takes `very' long to scan a directory.

By default @{b}ARCHandler@{ub} uses method 1: `Name and Contents'.

This  argument  overrides the method of archive recognition selected by the
@{"ONLYEXTENSION_ARG" link ONLYEXTENSION_ARG}

This  setting  can  also be changed with the @{"Archive Recognition" link RECOGNITION_GAD} gadget in
the @{"Archive Preferences" link ARCPREFS} window.
@endnode
@node TEMPDIR_ARG "ARCHandler: TEMPDIR argument"
@prev RECOGNITION_ARG
@next BUFFERS_ARG
@toc ARGUMENTS

  @{b}TEMPDIR@{ub}

When  you  (or a program) open a file in an archive, this file is extracted
and  temporarily  stored  in  a  directory.  When  the  file  is closed the
extracted file is deleted from the directory.

With the TEMPDIR argument you can specify which directory @{b}ARCHandler@{ub} should
use  to  store these temporary files. By default @{b}ARCHandler@{ub} uses `T:'. When
you  place this directory on the `Ram Disk:' files will be extracted faster
(by default `T:' is placed on `Ram Disk:').

This  setting  can  also be changed with the @{"Temporary Files" link TEMPFILES_GAD} gadget in the
@{"Archive Preferences" link ARCPREFS} window.
@endnode
@node BUFFERS_ARG "ARCHandler: BUFFERS argument"
@prev TEMPDIR_ARG
@next KEEPTIME_ARG
@toc ARGUMENTS

  @{b}BUFFERS@{ub}

Whenever  an  archive is accessed, @{b}ARCHandler@{ub} makes a list of all the files
and  directories  in  that archive (@{"archive-file-list" link FILELISTS}). This list is freed
when  this  information  is  no longer needed. Filerequesters and directory
utilities  tend  to  lock  a directory, scan its contents and then free the
lock.  When  one  of  the  subdirectories is selected, the filerequester or
directory utility will then lock that subdirectory and scan it.

To prevent @{b}ARCHandler@{ub} from remaking the list of files and directories in an
archive  on  each  archive access, a certain number of unused archive-lists
are kept in memory (in a least-recently-used cache).

With  the  BUFFERS  argument you specify the number of unused archive-lists
that  are  kept  in  memory.  This  should  be a number between 0 and 9. It
defaults to 2.

This  setting  can  also  be  changed  with  the  @{"Buffers" link BUFFERS_GAD}  gadget  in  the
@{"Archive Preferences" link ARCPREFS} window.
@endnode
@node KEEPTIME_ARG "ARCHandler: KEEPTIME argument"
@prev BUFFERS_ARG
@next LHACOMMAND_ARG

  @{b}KEEPTIME@{ub}

When  an  extracted archive is closed it isn't immediatly deleted. When the
same file is opened again the archive doesn't have to be reextracted.

With  the  KEEPTIME argument you can specify the time in seconds @{b}ARCHandler@{ub}
should wait before it deletes an extracted file after it is closed.

By default the extracted files are kept 2 seconds after they are closed.

This  setting  can  also  be  changed  with  the  @{"Keep Files" link KEEP_GAD} gadget in the
@{"Archive Preferences" link ARCPREFS} window.
@endnode
@node LHACOMMAND_ARG "ARCHandler: LHACOMMAND argument"
@prev KEEPTIME_ARG
@next IGNOREVOLUMES_ARG
@toc ARGUMENTS

  @{b}LHACOMMAND@{ub}

With  the  LHACOMMAND  you  can  specify the position of the `LhA' command.
Normally  @{b}ARCHandler@{ub}  will  find  `LhA'  if  it  is  placed  in  one of the
directories  that  C: is assigned to. If `LhA' is not in such a drawer, you
can specify the position with this argument.

When  you  use the included install script, it will search for the position
of `LhA' and write in in @{b}ARCHandlers@{ub} tooltype.

By  default  @{b}ARCHandler@{ub} uses `LhA', this will find `LhA' if it is placed in
one of the directories that C: is assigned to.

This argument can't be changed with the @{"graphical user interface" link GUI}, but when
@{b}ARCHandler@{ub} is installed the installation script will set this argument.
@endnode
@node IGNOREVOLUMES_ARG "ARCHandler: IGNOREVOLUMES argument"
@prev LHACOMMAND_ARG
@next ONLYEXTENSION_ARG
@toc ARGUMENTS

  @{b}IGNOREVOLUMES@{ub}

With this argument you can specify the volumes that should not be placed in
the filesystem's root directory.

This argument can't be changed with the @{"graphical user interface" link GUI}.
@endnode
@node ONLYEXTENSION_ARG "ARCHandler: ONLYEXTENSION option"
@prev IGNOREVOLUMES_ARG
@next ONLYEXTENSION_ARG
@toc ARGUMENTS

  @{b}ONLYEXTENSION@{ub}

This option is obsolete and superseded by the @{"RECOGNITION" link RECOGNITION_ARG} argument.

@{b}ARCHandler@{ub} still understands this argument, but RECOGNITION overrides it.
@endnode
@node WINDOWS "ARCHandler: Windows"
@prev ARGUMENTS
@next WORKBENCH

  @{b}@{u}ARCHandler Windows@{ub}@{uu}

The  @{b}ARCHandler@{ub}  @{"Graphical User Interface" link GUI}  consists  of  three windows and
three different kinds of requesters:

    @{" Main Window                  " link MAINWINDOW}
    @{" Device Preferences Window    " link DEVPREFS}
    @{" Archive Preferences Window   " link ARCPREFS}
    @{" Commodity Preferences Window " link CXPREFS}

    @{" Message Requesters         " link MSGREQ}
    @{" Directory Requesters       " link DIRREQ}
    @{" Key Combination Requesters " link KEYREQ}

The  windows  don't block each other: you're able to use several windows at
the same time. The requesters do block the window the originated from, this
window will receive a standard wait-pointer.
@endnode
@node MAINWINDOW "ARCHandler: Main Window"
@prev MAINWINDOW
@next DEVPREFS
@toc WINDOWS

  @{b}Main Window@{ub}

From  the  Main Window you can access the other windows. This window can be
opened by pressing the hot key; @{"CX_POPKEY" link CX_POPUP_ARG}, @{"HOTKEY" link HOTKEY_GAD}.

  @{"preview" link "/Pictures/ARCHandlerMain.pic/main"}

                      Preferences
      @{"  Device...  " link DEV_GAD} @{" Archive... " link ARC_GAD} @{" Commodity... " link CX_GAD}
      @{" Flush " link FLUSH_GAD} @{" About... " link ABOUT_GAD}

      @{" Hide " link HIDE_GAD}                             @{" Quit " link QUIT_GAD}


Menus:

  Project
    @{"About..." link ABOUT_GAD}
    @{"Help    " link MAINHELP_MENU}
    --------
    @{"Hide    " link HIDE_GAD}
    @{"Quit    " link QUIT_GAD}
@endnode
@node DEV_GAD "ARCHandler: MainWindow/Device gadget"
@prev DEV_GAD
@next ARC_GAD
@toc MAINWINDOW

  Device...

This gadget opens the @{"Device Preferences" link DEVPREFS} window.
@endnode
@node ARC_GAD "ARCHandler: MainWindow/Archive gadget"
@prev DEV_GAD
@next CX_GAD
@toc MAINWINDOW

  Archive...

This gadget opens the @{"Archive Preferences" link ARCPREFS} window.
@endnode
@node CX_GAD "ARCHandler: MainWindow/Commodity gadget"
@prev ARC_GAD
@next FLUSH_GAD
@toc MAINWINDOW

  Commodity...

This gadget opens the @{"Commodity Preferences" link CXPREFS} window.
@endnode
@node FLUSH_GAD "ARCHandler: Main Window/Flush gadget"
@prev CX_GAD
@next ABOUT_GAD
@toc MAINWINDOW

  Flush

You can use this gadget to flush unused @{"archive-lists" link FILELISTS} from memory.
@endnode
@node ABOUT_GAD "ARCHandler: Main Window/About gadget, About menu item"
@prev FLUSH_GAD
@next HIDE_GAD
@toc MAINWINDOW

  About...

This  will  open  a  @{"message requester" link MSGREQ}  that  gives some information about
@{b}ARCHandler@{ub}. It will tell you which language @{b}ARCHandler@{ub} is using and by whom
this version is registered.
@endnode
@node HIDE_GAD "ARCHandler: Main Window/Hide gadget, Hide menu item"
@prev ABOUT_GAD
@next QUIT_GAD
@toc MAINWINDOW

  Hide

When  this  gadget/menu item  is  used @{b}ARCHandler@{ub} will try to close all its
windows.  It  is  possible that some windows can not be closed because they
are blocked by a requester.
@endnode
@node QUIT_GAD "ARCHandler: Main Window/Quit gadget, Quit menu item"
@prev HIDE_GAD
@next MAINHELP_MENU
@toc MAINWINDOW

  Quit

With  this gadget/menu item you can @{"quit" link QUITTING} @{b}ARCHandler@{ub}. @{b}ARCHandler@{ub} will first
check  if nobody is still using @{b}ARCHandler@{ub}, after that it will try to close
all its windows.
@endnode
@node MAINHELP_MENU "ARCHandler: Main Window/Help menu item"
@prev QUIT_GAD
@next MAINHELP_MENU
@toc MAINWINDOW

  Help

When you select this menu and @{"context sensitive help" link HELP} is available you will
get some more information about the @{"Main Window" link MAINWINDOW}.
@endnode
@node DEVPREFS "ARCHandler: Device Preferences"
@prev MAINWINDOW
@next ARCPREFS
@toc WINDOWS

  @{b}Device Preferences Window@{ub}

The Device Preferences Window is used to change several device settings.

  @{"preview" link "/Pictures/ARCHandlerDevPrefs.pic/main"}

    Device Name @{" ARC         " link DEVNAME_GAD}      Task Priority @{"     # " link TASKPRI_GAD} 7
    Volume Name @{" Archives    " link VOLNAME_GAD}  Volume Scan Delay @{"  #  " link SCANDELAY_GAD} 4 s
    Extra Files @{" PROGDIR:ARCFiles                        " link EXTRAFILES_GAD}@{"v" link EXTRAFILES_GAD}

    @{" Save " link DEVSAVE_GAD}                  @{" Use " link DEVUSE_GAD}                 @{" Cancel " link DEVCANCEL_GAD}


Menus:

  Project
    @{"Help" link DEVHELP_MENU}

  Edit
    @{"Reset To Defaults" link DEVDEFAULTS_MENU}
    @{"Last Saved       " link DEVLASTSAVED_MENU}
    @{"Restore          " link DEVRESTORE_MENU}
@endnode
@node DEVNAME_GAD "ARCHandler: Device Preferences/Device Name gadget"
@prev DEVNAME_GAD
@next VOLNAME_GAD
@toc DEVPREFS

  Device Name

With  this  string  gadget  you  can  change  the  name  of  the @{b}ARCHandler@{ub}
DOS-device. The name of the DOS-device will only be changed when @{b}ARCHandler@{ub}
is restarted, so you should use @{"Save" link DEVSAVE_GAD} when you change this.

When  the  settings  are saved the Device Name is stored in the @{"DEVICENAME" link DEVICENAME_ARG}
argument.
@endnode
@node VOLNAME_GAD "ARCHandler: Device Preferences/Volume Name gadget"
@prev DEVNAME_GAD
@next TASKPRI_GAD
@toc DEVPREFS

  Volume Name

With  this  string gadget you can change the name of the @{b}ARCHandler@{ub} volume.
When  you  @{"Use" link DEVUSE_GAD}  this  new  name, this has the same effect as the `Relabel'
command.

When  the  settings  are saved the Volume Name is stored in the @{"VOLUMENAME" link VOLUMENAME_ARG}
argument.
@endnode
@node TASKPRI_GAD "ARCHandler: Device Preferences/Task Priority gadget"
@prev VOLNAME_GAD
@next SCANDELAY_GAD
@toc DEVPREFS

  Task Priority

With  this slider gadget you select the priority of the @{b}ARCHandler@{ub} process.
This  process  handles  all  the  @{"filesystem" link FILESYSTEM}  actions and also handles the
@{"windows" link WINDOWS}.  The priority  should  be  a  number  between  -5  and +15. By
specifying  a  higher  number,  the  filesystem will have a @{i}relative @{ui}faster
response time on a @{i}busy system.@{ui}

Normally,  filesystems  have a higher priority then other processes because
other  processes  have to wait on these filesystems.

Note that this priority does not change the extraction time of archives. To
extract archives, @{b}ARCHandler@{ub} generates a new process at priority zero.

When  the  settings  are  saved  the  priority  is  stored in the @{"PRIORITY" link PRIORITY_ARG}
argument.
@endnode
@node SCANDELAY_GAD "ARCHandler: Device Preferences/Volume Scan Delay gadget"
@prev TASKPRI_GAD
@next EXTRAFILES_GAD
@toc DEVPREFS

  Volume Scan Delay

Because  the @{b}ARCHandler@{ub} @{"filesystem" link FILESYSTEM} has all the volumes in its root volume,
it  has  to  scan  the AmigaDOS list of volumes. Because new volumes can be
created  or  inserted,  or  the name of the current volumes can be changed,
this  scanning has to be repeated. Normally, when a new volume is inserted,
its  filesystem  will  generate a DISKINSERTED event (or DISKREMOVED when a
volume  is removed). @{b}ARCHandler@{ub} will also catch these events and then start
to scan the AmigaDOS volume list.

This  slider  gadget  is  used to select the number of seconds between each
AmigaDOS volume list scan.

When  the  settings  are  saved  the scan delay is stored in the @{"SCANDELAY" link SCANDELAY_ARG}
argument.
@endnode
@node EXTRAFILES_GAD "ARCHandler: Device Preferences/Extra Files gadget"
@prev SCANDELAY_GAD
@next DEVSAVE_GAD
@toc DEVPREFS

  Extra Files

To  make  it easy to access files from the @{"Workbench" link WORKBENCH}, @{b}ARCHandler@{ub} adds some
extra files to the filesystem.

You  can  use  the  Extra  Files string-gadget to change this directory. By
pressing  the  popup-gadget  behind  the  string-gadget  you  can  use  the
@{"Directory Requester" link DIRREQ} to pick this directory.

When  the  settings  are  saved  the extra files directory is stored in the
@{"FILESDIR" link TEMPDIR_ARG} argument.
@endnode
@node DEVSAVE_GAD "ARCHandler: Device Preferences/Save gadget"
@prev EXTRAFILES_GAD
@next DEVUSE_GAD
@toc DEVPREFS

  Save

You  can  use this gadget to permanently save the Device Preferences. These
settings will be saved in the tooltypes of the @{b}ARCHandler@{ub}-icon.
@endnode
@node DEVUSE_GAD "ARCHandler: Device Preferences/Use gadget"
@prev DEVSAVE_GAD
@next DEVCANCEL_GAD
@toc DEVPREFS

  Use

When  you  use  this gadget to close the @{"Device Preferences window" link DEVPREFS} the new
settings will be used but not saved.
@endnode
@node DEVCANCEL_GAD "ARCHandler: Device Preferences/Cancel gadget"
@prev DEVUSE_GAD
@next DEVHELP_MENU
@toc DEVPREFS

  Cancel

When you select this gadget to leave the @{"Device Preferences window" link DEVPREFS} all the
changes that you made to the Device Preferences will be discarded. The same
thing happens when you use the windows close-gadget.
@endnode
@node DEVHELP_MENU "ARCHandler: Device Preferences Window/Help menu item"
@prev DEVCANCEL_GAD
@next DEVDEFAULTS_MENU
@toc DEVPREFS

  Help

When you select this menu and @{"context sensitive help" link HELP} is available you will
get some more information about the @{"Device Preferences Window" link DEVPREFS}.
@endnode
@node DEVDEFAULTS_MENU "ARCHandler: Device Preferences Window/Reset To Defaults menu item"
@prev DEVHELP_MENU
@next DEVLASTSAVED_MENU
@toc DEVPREFS

  Reset To Defaults

When  you  select  this  menu  item,  the  values  in  the  gadgets  of the
@{"Device Preferences Window" link DEVPREFS} will be changed to the default values. This will
not change the settings, only the values in the gadgets.

The defaults for the Device Preferences are:

    @{" Device Name       " link DEVNAME_GAD} "ARC"
    @{" Volume Name       " link VOLNAME_GAD} "Archives"
    @{" Task Priority     " link TASKPRI_GAD} 5
    @{" Volume Scan Delay " link SCANDELAY_GAD} 4 sec
    @{" Extra Files       " link EXTRAFILES_GAD} "PROGDIR:ARCFiles"
@endnode
@node DEVLASTSAVED_MENU "ARCHandler: Device Preferences Window/Last Saved menu item"
@prev DEVDEFAULTS_MENU
@next DEVRESTORE_MENU
@toc DEVPREFS

  Last Saved

This  will  read the settings that were last saved on place those values in
the  gadgets  of  the  @{"Device Preferences Window" link DEVPREFS}. This will not change the
settings, only the values in the gadgets.
@endnode
@node DEVRESTORE_MENU "ARCHandler: Device Preferences Window/Restore menu item"
@prev DEVLASTSAVED_MENU
@next DEVRESTORE_MENU
@toc DEVPREFS

  Restore

This  will  place the settings that are currently in use, in the gadgets of
the @{"Device Preferences Window" link DEVPREFS}. This will not change the settings, only the
values in the gadgets.
@endnode
@node ARCPREFS "ARCHandler: Archive Preferences"
@prev DEVPREFS
@next CXPREFS
@toc WINDOWS

  @{b}Archive Preferences Window@{ub}

The Archive Preferences Window is used to change several archive settings.

  @{"preview" link "/Pictures/ARCHandlerArcPrefs.pic/main"}

    Archive Recognition @{"Name and Contents" link RECOGNITION_GAD}        Buffers @{"  #     " link BUFFERS_GAD} 2
        Temporary Files @{" T:                " link TEMPFILES_GAD}@{"v" link TEMPFILES_GAD}  Keep File @{"  #  " link KEEP_GAD} 2 sec

    @{" Save " link ARCSAVE_GAD}                      @{" Use " link ARCUSE_GAD}                     @{" Cancel " link ARCCANCEL_GAD}


Menus:

  Project
    @{"Help" link ARCHELP_MENU}

  Edit
    @{"Reset To Defaults" link ARCDEFAULTS_MENU}
    @{"Last Saved       " link ARCLASTSAVED_MENU}
    @{"Restore          " link ARCRESTORE_MENU}
@endnode
@node RECOGNITION_GAD "ARCHandler: Archive Preferences/Archive Recognition cycle gadget"
@prev RECOGNITION_GAD
@next TEMPFILES_GAD
@toc ARCPREFS

  Archive Recognition

With the Recognition cycle gadget you can select the method that @{b}ARCHandler@{ub}
uses to recognize archive.

`Filename only'
    @{b}ARCHandler@{ub}  will  only  look  at  the name of the files to recognize an
    archive (eg. an @{"LhA-archives" link LHA} has a file-extension `.lha' or `.lzh').

    This  will  give the fastest access to directories. But it can make the
    wrong decision.

`Name and Contents'
    @{b}ARCHandler@{ub}  first  checks  the  name of file (like in `Filename only'),
    after that it opens the file to see if it is really an archive.

    This will always make the right decision (except corrupt archives), but
    it  takes  much  longer  to  scan  a directory: it will first check the
    filename and if that matches it will open the file.

`File Contents'
    @{b}ARCHandler@{ub}  will only look at the contents of a file to decide if it is
    an archive.

    The  file will always be opened (without looking at the filename). This
    allows  you  to  give any name to the archive. Since all the files in a
    directory have to be opened it takes `very' long to scan a directory.

This  option  isn't  used  when you try to create a new archive. @{b}ARCHandler@{ub}
will  always  look  at  the  name of the new directory to decide if it will
become an archive.

When  the  settings  are  saved  the  state  is  stored in the @{"RECOGNITION" link RECOGNITION_ARG}
argument.
@endnode
@node TEMPFILES_GAD "ARCHandler: Archive Preferences/Temporary Files gadget"
@prev RECOGNITION_GAD
@next BUFFERS_GAD
@toc ARCPREFS

  Temporary Files

When  you  (or a program) open a file in an archive, this file is extracted
and  temporarily  stored  in  a  directory.  When  the  file  is closed the
extracted file is deleted from the directory.

With  the  Temporary  Files  string-gadget  you can specify which directory
@{b}ARCHandler@{ub}  should  use  to  store  these  temporary files. By pressing the
popup-gadget  behind the string-gadget you can use the @{"Directory Requester" link DIRREQ}
to pick this directory.

When  the settings are saved the temporary files directory is stored in the
@{"TEMPDIR" link TEMPDIR_ARG} argument.
@endnode
@node BUFFERS_GAD "ARCHandler: Archive Preferences/Buffers gadget"
@prev TEMPFILES_GAD
@next KEEP_GAD
@toc ARCPREFS

  Buffers

Whenever  an  archive is accessed, @{b}ARCHandler@{ub} makes a list of all the files
and  directories  in  that archive (@{"archive-file-list" link FILELISTS}). This list is freed
when  this  information  is  no longer needed. Filerequesters and directory
utilities  tend  to  lock  a directory, scan its contents and then free the
lock.  When  one  of  the  subdirectories is selected, the filerequester or
directory utility will then lock that subdirectory and scan it.

To prevent @{b}ARCHandler@{ub} from remaking the list of files and directories in an
archive  on  each  archive access, a certain number of unused archive-lists
are kept in memory (in a least-recently-used cache).

With this slider gadget you select the number of unused @{"archive-file-lists" link FILELISTS}
that are kept in memory.

When  the  settings are saved the number of archive-file-lists is stored in
the @{"BUFFERS" link BUFFERS_ARG} argument.
@endnode
@node KEEP_GAD "ARCHandler: Archive Preferences/Keep Files gadget"
@prev BUFFERS_GAD
@next ARCUSE_GAD
@toc ARCPREFS

  Keep Files

When  an  extracted archive is closed it isn't immediatly deleted. When the
same file is opened again the archive doesn't have to be reextracted.

With  this  slider  gadget  you can specify the time @{b}ARCHandler@{ub} should wait
before it deletes an extracted file after it is closed.

When  the  settings  are  saved  the  number  of  seconds  is stored in the
@{"KEEPTIME" link KEEPTIME_ARG} argument.
@endnode
@node ARCSAVE_GAD "ARCHandler: Archive Preferences/Save gadget"
@prev KEEP_GAD
@next ARCUSE_GAD
@toc ARCPREFS

  Save

You  can use this gadget to permanently save the Archive Preferences. These
settings will be saved in the tooltypes of the @{b}ARCHandler@{ub}-icon.
@endnode
@node ARCUSE_GAD "ARCHandler: Archive Preferences/Use gadget"
@prev ARCSAVE_GAD
@next ARCCANCEL_GAD
@toc ARCPREFS

  Use

When  you  use this gadget to close the @{"Archive Preferences window" link ARCPREFS} the new
settings will be used but not saved.
@endnode
@node ARCCANCEL_GAD "ARCHandler: Archive Preferences/Cancel gadget"
@prev ARCUSE_GAD
@next ARCHELP_MENU
@toc ARCPREFS

  Cancel

When  you  select  this gadget to leave the @{"Archive Preferences window" link ARCPREFS} all
the changes that you made to the Archive Preferences will be discarded. The
same thing happens when you use the windows close-gadget.
@endnode
@node ARCHELP_MENU "ARCHandler: Archive Preferences Window/Help menu item"
@prev ARCCANCEL_GAD
@next ARCDEFAULTS_MENU
@toc ARCPREFS

  Help

When you select this menu and @{"context sensitive help" link HELP} is available you will
get some more information about the @{"Archive Preferences Window" link ARCPREFS}.
@endnode
@node ARCDEFAULTS_MENU "ARCHandler: Archive Preferences Window/Reset To Defaults menu item"
@prev ARCHELP_MENU
@next ARCLASTSAVED_MENU
@toc ARCPREFS

  Reset To Defaults

When  you  select  this  menu  item,  the  values  in  the  gadgets  of the
@{"Archive Preferences Window" link ARCPREFS}  will  be  changed  to the default values. This
will not change the settings, only the values in the gadgets.

The defaults for the Archive Preferences are:

    @{" Archive Recognition " link RECOGNITION_GAD} "Name and Contents"
    @{" Temporary Files     " link TEMPFILES_GAD} "T:"
    @{" Buffers             " link BUFFERS_GAD} 2
    @{" Keep File           " link KEEP_GAD} 2 sec
@endnode
@node ARCLASTSAVED_MENU "ARCHandler: Archive Preferences Window/Last Saved menu item"
@prev ARCDEFAULTS_MENU
@next ARCRESTORE_MENU
@toc ARCPREFS

  Last Saved

This  will  read the settings that were last saved on place those values in
the  gadgets  of  the  @{"Archive Preferences Window" link ARCPREFS}. This will not change the
settings, only the values in the gadgets.
@endnode
@node ARCRESTORE_MENU "ARCHandler: Archive Preferences Window/Restore menu item"
@prev ARCLASTSAVED_MENU
@next ARCRESTORE_MENU
@toc ARCPREFS

  Restore

This  will  place the settings that are currently in use, in the gadgets of
the  @{"Archive Preferences Window" link ARCPREFS}.  This  will not change the settings, only
the values in the gadgets.
@endnode
@node CXPREFS "ARCHandler: Commodity Preferences"
@prev ARCPREFS
@next MSGREQ
@toc WINDOWS

  @{b}Commodity Preferences Window@{ub}

The  Commodity  Preferences  Window  is  used  to  change several commodity
settings.

  @{"preview" link "/Pictures/ARCHandlerCxPrefs.pic/main"}

        Hot Key @{" Ctrl Alt a                  " link HOTKEY_GAD}@{"v" link HOTKEY_GAD}
      Flush Key @{" Ctrl Alt f                  " link FLUSHKEY_GAD}@{"v" link FLUSHKEY_GAD}
       Priority @{"             #               " link CX_PRIORITY_GAD} 0
         Pop up @{"  " link POPUP_GAD}

      @{" Save " link CXSAVE_GAD}           @{" Use " link CXUSE_GAD}          @{" Cancel " link CXCANCEL_GAD}


Menus:

  Project
    @{"Help" link CXHELP_MENU}

  Edit
    @{"Reset To Defaults" link CXDEFAULTS_MENU}
    @{"Last Saved       " link CXLASTSAVED_MENU}
    @{"Restore          " link CXRESTORE_MENU}
@endnode
@node HOTKEY_GAD "ARCHandler: Commodity Preferences/Hot Key gadget"
@prev HOTKEY_GAD
@next FLUSHKEY_GAD
@toc CXPREFS

  Hot Key

This  string-gadget  is used to change the key combination that can be used
to  pop  up  @{b}ARCHandler's@{ub} @{"Main Window" link MAINWINDOW}. By pressing the popup-gadget behind
the  string-gadget  you can use the @{"Key Combination Requester" link KEYREQ} to pick this
key description.

When you specify an empty string @{b}ARCHandler@{ub} won't generate a pop up key.

When  the  settings  are  saved  the hot key description is stored in the
@{"CX_POPKEY" link CX_POPKEY_ARG} argument.
@endnode
@node FLUSHKEY_GAD "ARCHandler: Commodity Preferences/Flush Key gadget"
@prev HOTKEY_GAD
@next CX_PRIORITY_GAD
@toc CXPREFS

  Flush Key

This  string-gadget  is used to change the key combination that can be used
to  flush  all  the unused @{"archive-file-lists" link FILELISTS} from memory. By pressing the
popup-gadget     behind    the    string-gadget    you    can    use    the
@{"Key Combination Requester" link KEYREQ} to pick this key description.

When you specify an empty string for this argument, @{b}ARCHandler@{ub} won't create
a flush key.

When  the  settings  are  saved  the flush key description is stored in the
@{"FLUSHKEY" link FLUSHKEY_ARG} argument.
@endnode
@node CX_PRIORITY_GAD "ARCHandler: Commodity Preferences/Priority gadget"
@prev FLUSHKEY_GAD
@next POPUP_GAD
@toc CXPREFS

  Priority

With this slider-gadget you select the priority of the @{b}ARCHandler@{ub} Commodity
in the chain of all the running commodities.

The  priority  of  the  commodity  will  only be changed when @{b}ARCHandler@{ub} is
restarted, so you should use @{"Save" link CXSAVE_GAD} when you change this.

When  the  settings  are  saved  the priority is stored in the @{"CX_PRIORITY" link CX_PRIORITY_ARG}
argument.
@endnode
@node POPUP_GAD "ARCHandler: Commodity Preferences/Pop Up gadget"
@prev CX_PRIORITY_GAD
@next CXSAVE_GAD
@toc CXPREFS

  Pop Up

With  checkbox  you  can  choose if @{b}ARCHandler@{ub} will pop up its @{"Main Window" link MAINWINDOW}
when it is started.

When  the  settings  are  saved  the popup-state is stored in the @{"CX_POPUP" link CX_POPUP_ARG}
argument.
@endnode
@node CXSAVE_GAD "ARCHandler: Commodity Preferences/Save gadget"
@prev POPUP_GAD
@next CXUSE_GAD
@toc CXPREFS

  Save

You  can  use  this  gadget  to permanently save the Commodity Preferences.
These settings will be saved in the tooltypes of the @{b}ARCHandler@{ub}-icon.
@endnode
@node CXUSE_GAD "ARCHandler: Commodity Preferences/Use gadget"
@prev CXSAVE_GAD
@next CXCANCEL_GAD
@toc CXPREFS

  Use

When you use this gadget to close the @{"Commodity Preferences window" link CXPREFS} the new
settings will be used but not saved.
@endnode
@node CXCANCEL_GAD "ARCHandler: Commodity Preferences/Cancel gadget"
@prev CXUSE_GAD
@next CXHELP_MENU
@toc CXPREFS

  Cancel

When  you select this gadget to leave the @{"Commodity Preferences window" link CXPREFS} all
the  changes  that you made to the Commodity Preferences will be discarded.
The same thing happens when you use the windows close-gadget.
@endnode
@node CXHELP_MENU "ARCHandler: Commodity Preferences Window/Help menu item"
@prev CXCANCEL_GAD
@next CXDEFAULTS_MENU
@toc CXPREFS

  Help

When you select this menu and @{"context sensitive help" link HELP} is available you will
get some more information about the @{"Commodity Preferences Window" link CXPREFS}.
@endnode
@node CXDEFAULTS_MENU "ARCHandler: Commodity Preferences Window/Reset To Defaults menu item"
@prev CXHELP_MENU
@next CXLASTSAVED_MENU
@toc CXPREFS

  Reset To Defaults

When  you  select  this  menu  item,  the  values  in  the  gadgets  of the
@{"Commodity Preferences Window" link CXPREFS}  will  be changed to the default values. This
will not change the settings, only the values in the gadgets.

The defaults for the Commodity Preferences are:

    @{" Hot Key   " link HOTKEY_GAD} "Ctrl Alt a" (or "Control Alt a" for Workbench 2.04)
    @{" Flush Key " link FLUSHKEY_GAD} "Ctrl Alt f" (or "Control Alt f" for Workbench 2.04)
    @{" Priority  " link CX_PRIORITY_GAD} 0
    @{" Pop up    " link POPUP_GAD} "Yes"
@endnode
@node CXLASTSAVED_MENU "ARCHandler: Commodity Preferences Window/Last Saved menu item"
@prev CXDEFAULTS_MENU
@next CXRESTORE_MENU
@toc CXPREFS

  Last Saved

This  will  read the settings that were last saved on place those values in
the  gadgets  of  the  @{"Commodity Preferences Window" link CXPREFS}. This will not change the
settings, only the values in the gadgets.
@endnode
@node CXRESTORE_MENU "ARCHandler: Commodity Preferences Window/Restore menu item"
@prev CXLASTSAVED_MENU
@next CXRESTORE_MENU
@toc CXPREFS

  Restore

This  will  place the settings that are currently in use, in the gadgets of
the  @{"Commodity Preferences Window" link CXPREFS}. This will not change the settings, only
the values in the gadgets.
@endnode
@node MSGREQ "ARCHandler: Message Requesters"
@prev CXPREFS
@next DIRREQ
@toc WINDOWS

  @{b}Message Requesters@{ub}

@{b}ARCHandler@{ub}  uses  several  Message Requesters to communicate with the user.
These requester are fully keyboard controlable. The shortcuts are specified
by  the  underscored  characters  in the gadgets. The default gadget has an
extra dark border.

  @{" About                         " link ABOUT_REQ} 
  @{" ARCHandler can't quit         " link NOQUIT_REQ}
  @{" Archive is corrupt            " link ARCCORRUPT_REQ}
  @{" Name has colon                " link NAMECOLON_REQ}
  @{" Can't lock as directory       " link NOLOCKDIR_REQ}
  @{" Directory shouldn't be on ARC " link ONARC_REQ}
  @{" Is not a directory            " link NODIR_REQ}
  @{" Key can't be created          " link NOKEY_REQ}
  @{" LhA not found                 " link NOLHA_REQ}
  @{" Setting can't be changed      " link NOSETTING_REQ}
  @{" Settings couldn't be saved    " link NOSAVE_REQ}

When   something   is  wrong  with  the  underlying  filesystem  ('disk  is
write-protected',  'volume  not  mounted' ...), @{b}ARCHandler@{ub} will also try to
report  this. It uses a normal Message Requesters, but these requesters can
also be satisfied by inserting a disk.
@endnode
@node ABOUT_REQ "ARCHandler: Message Requester/About"
@prev ABOUT_REQ
@next NOQUIT_REQ
@toc MSGREQ

  About

This requester tells you which version of @{b}ARCHandler@{ub} you are using and what
language it is using.
@endnode
@node NOQUIT_REQ "ARCHandler: Message Requester/ARCHandler can't quit"
@prev ABOUT_REQ
@next ARCCORRUPT_REQ
@toc MSGREQ

  ARCHandler can't quit

This  requester  will  be  used  when you ask @{b}ARCHandler@{ub} to @{"quit" link QUITTING} (with the
@{"Quit" link QUIT_GAD}-gadget,  with  the Exchange program or by sending a ACTION_KILL), but
@{b}ARCHandler@{ub}  isn't  able  to  quit.  The  requester  text  will tell you why
@{b}ARCHandler@{ub} can't quit at that moment.

When  you  ask  @{b}ARCHandler@{ub} to quit it will try to close all its windows. It
may not be able to close a window because it is locked by a requester.

It  is  also  possible that @{b}ARCHandler@{ub} can't quit because somebody is still
using  the  @{b}ARCHandler@{ub} @{"filesystem" link FILESYSTEM}. In this case the requester will contain
the number of files, locks and/or archives that are still in use.

When  a  program  crashes  while  it  is  using  the @{b}ARCHandler@{ub} filesystem,
@{b}ARCHandler@{ub} will never be able to quit.
@endnode
@node ARCCORRUPT_REQ "ARCHandler: Message Requester/Archive is corrupt"
@prev NOQUIT_REQ
@next NAMECOLON_REQ
@toc MSGREQ

  Archive is corrupt

This  requester  is  used  when  an  archive is corrupt or is not really an
archive (check @{"RECOGNITION" link RECOGNITION_ARG} argument or @{"Recognition" link RECOGNITION_GAD} gadget).
@endnode
@node NAMECOLON_REQ "ARCHandler: Message Requester/Name has colon"
@next NOLOCKDIR_REQ
@prev ARCCORRUPT_REQ
@toc MSGREQ

  Name has colon

The @{"Device Name" link DEVNAME_GAD} or the @{"Volume Name" link VOLNAME_GAD} should not contain a colon (`:').
@endnode
@node NOLOCKDIR_REQ "ARCHandler: Message Requester/Can't lock as directory"
@prev NAMECOLON_REQ
@next ONARC_REQ
@toc MSGREQ

  Can't lock as directory

The  directory you specified in the @{"Temporary Files" link TEMPFILES_GAD} or @{"Extra Files" link EXTRAFILES_GAD} string-
gadget does no exist or it couldn't be accessed.
@endnode
@node ONARC_REQ "ARCHandler: Message Requester/Directory shouldn't be on ARC"
@prev NOLOCKDIR_REQ
@next NODIR_REQ
@toc MSGREQ

  Directory shouldn't be on ARC

The  directory you specified in the @{"Temporary Files" link TEMPFILES_GAD} or @{"Extra Files" link EXTRAFILES_GAD} string-
gadget  is  placed on the ARC @{"filesystem" link FILESYSTEM}. Both these directories should be
placed on a filesystem that @{b}ARCHandler@{ub} can use directly.
@endnode
@node NODIR_REQ "ARCHandler: Message Requester/Is not a directory"
@prev ONARC_REQ
@next NODIR_REQ
@toc MSGREQ

  Is not a directory

The  path  you  specified  in  the  @{"Temporary Files" link TEMPFILES_GAD} or @{"Extra Files" link EXTRAFILES_GAD} string-
gadget is not a directory.
@endnode
@node NOKEY_REQ "ARCHandler: Message Requester/Key can't be created"
@prev NODIR_REQ
@next NOKEY_REQ
@toc MSGREQ

  Key can't be created

The key description you specified in @{"Hot Key" link HOTKEY_GAD} or @{"Flush Key" link FLUSHKEY_GAD} string-gadget is
not valid, or there wasn't enough memory to create the commodity object.
@endnode
@node NOLHA_REQ "ARCHandler: Message Requester/LhA not found"
@prev NOKEY_REQ
@next NOSETTING_REQ
@toc MSGREQ

  LhA not found

@{b}ARCHandler@{ub}  needs  LhA  to  extract files from @{"lha" link LHA}-archives. When you have
used  the  Install  script  to  install @{b}ARCHandler@{ub} the @{"LHACOMMAND" link LHACOMMAND_ARG} tooltype
should contain the correct path of LhA. If you have changed the position of
LhA  or  haven't used the included Install script, @{b}ARCHandler@{ub} won't be able
to  find  LhA. You should use the LHACOMMAND-tooltype to tell @{b}ARCHandler@{ub} to
full path to @{b}ARCHandler@{ub} (use `Work:Tools/LhA' and not `Work:Tools/').
@endnode
@node NOSETTING_REQ "ARCHandler: Message Requester/Setting can't be changed"
@prev NOLHA_REQ
@next NOSAVE_REQ
@toc MSGREQ

  Setting can't be changed

The  name  of  the  DOS-device  and  the priority of the commodity can't be
changed  while  @{b}ARCHandler@{ub}  is running. When you change these settings with
the  @{"Device Name" link DEVNAME_GAD}  string-gadget  or the @{"Priority" link CX_PRIORITY_GAD} slider-gadget, @{b}ARCHandler@{ub}
will use this requester to inform you that these settings are not changed.
@endnode
@node NOSAVE_REQ "ARCHandler: Message Requester/Settings couldn't be saved"
@prev NOSETTING_REQ
@next NOSAVE_REQ
@toc MSGREQ

  Settings couldn't be saved

The requester will contain the specific reason why the settings couldn't be
saved. When @{b}ARCHandler@{ub} is started from the CLI it won't be able to save its
settings when there's no icon for the program.
@endnode
@node DIRREQ "ARCHandler: Directory Requesters"
@prev MSGREQ
@next KEYREQ
@toc WINDOWS

  @{b}Directory Requesters@{ub}

The  @{"Temporary Files" link TEMPFILES_GAD}  or  @{"Extra Files" link EXTRAFILES_GAD}  string-gadget can be changed with a
directory   requester.   When   you   press  the  popup-gadget  behind  the
string-gadget  a  directory  requester  will be opened. This requester will
block the @{"Device Preferences" link DEVPREFS} window.
@endnode
@node KEYREQ "ARCHandler: Key Combination Requesters"
@prev DIRREQ
@next KEYREQ
@toc WINDOWS

  @{b}Key Combination Requesters@{ub}

The  @{"Hot Key" link HOTKEY_GAD}  or  @{"Flush Key" link FLUSHKEY_GAD}  string-gadget  can  be  changed  with the key
requester.  This  requester  allows  you  to  specify  a key combination by
pressing that key/those keys on the keyboard.

  @{"preview" link "/Pictures/ARCHandlerKeyReq.pic/main"}

     @{" Get " link KGET_GAD}@{" Nothing " link KNOTHING_GAD}@{"            " link KKEY_GAD}

     @{" Ok " link KOK_GAD}               @{" Cancel " link KCANCEL_GAD}
    
This requester will block the @{"Commodity Preferences" link CXPREFS} window.
@endnode
@node KGET_GAD "ARCHandler: Key Combination Requesters/Get gadget"
@prev KGET_GAD
@next KNOTHING_GAD
@toc KEYREQ

  Get

You  can  use this gadget to activate the @{"key combination gadget" link KKEY_GAD}. When you
press  the  `Get'  button,  the requester will use the next key combination
that you press.
@endnode
@node KNOTHING_GAD "ARCHandler: Key Combination Requesters/Nothing gadget"
@prev KGET_GAD
@next KKEY_GAD
@toc KEYREQ

  Nothing

With  the  `Nothing' button you can delete the current key combination. You
can  use  this  when you don't want to use a key combination for @{"Pop Up" link HOTKEY_GAD} or
@{"Flush" link FLUSHKEY_GAD}.
@endnode
@node KKEY_GAD "ARCHandler: Key Combination Requesters/Key Combination Gaget"
@prev KNOTHING_GAD
@next KOK_GAD
@toc KEYREQ

  Key Combination gadget

When  you  activate the key combination gadget, either by pressing the @{"Get" link KGET_GAD}
gadget or by pressing in the key combination gadget, the requester will use
the next key combination that you press.
@endnode
@node KOK_GAD "ARCHandler: Key Combination Requesters/Ok gadget"
@prev KKEY_GAD
@next KCANCEL_GAD
@toc KEYREQ

  Ok

When  you leave the Key Combination Requester with the `Ok' button, the key
combination  that  is in the requester will be copied to the string gadget;
@{"Hot Key" link HOTKEY_GAD} or @{"Flush Key" link FLUSHKEY_GAD}.
@endnode
@node KCANCEL_GAD "ARCHandler: Key Combination Requesters/Cancel gadget"
@prev KOK_GAD
@next KCANCEL_GAD
@toc KEYREQ

  Cancel

When  you leave the Key Combination Requester with the `Ok' button, the key
combination in the string gadget (@{"Hot Key" link HOTKEY_GAD} or @{"Flush Key" link FLUSHKEY_GAD}) won't be changed.
@endnode
@node WORKBENCH "ARCHandler: Workbench Support"
@prev WINDOWS
@next SUPPORT

  @{b}@{u}Workbench support@{ub}@{uu}

To  be  able  to  easily  access  the @{b}ARCHandler@{ub} through the Workbench, the
handler adds extra files:

 ·In  the root of the @{b}ARCHandler@{ub} volume there is a disk-icon `Disk.info'.
  You  can  `Snapshot'  the  position  of  the  icon  and the window (use
  `Snapshot» Window') and you can edit the icon (with IconEdit).

 ·In  the  root  of  the volume there are also drawer-icons for the other
  volumes.  These  icons  are created from the original disk-icon on that
  volume.  If  this icon does not exist, @{b}ARCHandler@{ub} will use it's default
  volume-icon  (if  this  default icon does not exist the volumes without
  there  own  disk-icon will not be visible from the Workbench). Only the
  icon  of  volumes that don't have there own disk-icon can be written to
  (but  @{b}ARCHandler@{ub}  will  always remove the position information in these
  icons, otherwise they would overlap).

 ·For  all  the  archives  the handler recognizes a drawer-icon is added.
  You  can  write  to  this  icon,  but  the  @{"filesystem" link FILESYSTEM} will remove the
  position information (otherwise all archive-icons would overlap). These
  icons can't be deleted (the filesystem won't complain when you try, but
  nothing happens).

 ·In  the root of the filesystem a `.backdrop'-file is added. You can use
  this file to `Leave Out' (`Icons' menu item of the Workbench) files and
  drawers.

All  these  files are stored in the @{"FILESDIR" link FILESDIR_ARG} directory. The `archive-icon'
is  stored  in the `Drawer.info' file and the default volume-icon is stored
in  `Volume.info'.  If  you  want to change these files it's best to change
them through the @{b}ARCHandler@{ub} filesystem.

You  can  also add other files to the @{"FILESDIR" link FILESDIR_ARG} directory, you will then be
able  to  access  these files from the root-directory. These files won't be
visible  in  the  root-directory  (`List ARC:' won't show these files); you
could use this to add a `Node.rinfo' file, for the ParNET package.
@endnode
@node TIPS "ARCHandler: Tips for Using"
@prev WORKBENCH
@next SUPPORT

  @{b}@{u}Tips for Using ARCHandler@{ub}@{uu}

    @{" Online help              " link HELP}
    @{" Faster ARCHandler        " link FASTER}
    @{" Quitting ARCHandler      " link QUITTING}
    @{" MultiUser and ARCHandler " link MULTIUSER}
@endnode
@node HELP "ARCHandler: Online Help"
@prev HELP
@next FASTER
@toc TIPS

  @{b}Online Help@{ub}

@{b}ARCHandler@{ub}  is  able  to  give you help on the current window or requester:
activate the window or requester and press the `Help' key.

To  be  able to use the online help, the documentation should be installed.
The install script allows you to install the documentation. @{b}ARCHandler@{ub} will
only load the documentation after you have pressed the `Help' key.

Online  help  is  available  in all windows and requesters (except the file
requester).

I  you  didn't  choose to install the 'Help files' then @{b}ARCHandler@{ub} won't be
able to open this document, and I won't give you any help.
@endnode
@node FASTER "ARCHandler: Faster"
@prev HELP
@next QUITTING
@toc TIPS

  @{b}Faster ARCHandler@{ub}

You  can  speed-up  the  extraction  of files by making LhA resident. Add a
`Resident  >NIL:  <path-to-lha>/LhA'  to your `User-Startup' and change the
@{"LHACOMMAND" link LHACOMMAND_ARG} to `LhA' (without path).

A  diskcache  on the volume that you are accessing will also give you a big
speed increase.
@endnode
@node QUITTING "ARCHandler: Quitting"
@prev FASTER
@next MULTIUSER
@toc TIPS

  @{b}Quitting ARCHandler@{ub}

Before  you can quit @{b}ARCHandler@{ub} you should quit all programs that are using
@{b}ARCHandler@{ub},  or at least change there current-directory and close any files
that they are using on the filesystem.

When  @{b}ARCHandler@{ub}  is  asked  to  quit  it  will  simulate a disk removal to
encourage  all  programs using @{b}ARCHandler@{ub} to free the locks the have on the
@{"filesystem" link FILESYSTEM}  and  it  will  start  to free its own resources. Some programs
don't  support this (for example a shell with a directory on the filesystem
as  its  current  directory).  If  you  are  in  this situation you can ask
@{b}ARCHandler@{ub} to reactivate itself so the filesystem can be used again.

@{b}ARCHandler@{ub}  can be reactivated by pressing the hotkey (@{"CX_POPKEY" link CX_POPUP_ARG}, @{"HOTKEY" link HOTKEY_GAD}),
by  activating  the  commodity  from  the  Exchange program or by sending a
ACTION_DISK_CHANGE (DiskChange) packet

Note  that  it is possibly dangerous to remove the filesystem. I have never
had  any trouble when quitting @{b}ARCHandler@{ub}. But, since @{b}ARCHandler@{ub} can't know
if  another  process has called DeviceProc() on it, it is possible that the
other process uses the returned message-port after @{b}ARCHandler@{ub} has quit.

When a program that was using @{b}ARCHandler@{ub} crashed before it was able to free
all the locks and files @{b}ARCHandler@{ub} will never be able to quit.
@endnode
@node MULTIUSER "ARCHandler: MultiUser"
@prev QUITTING
@next MULTIUSER
@toc TIPS

  @{b}MultiUser and ARCHandler@{ub}

Currently  @{b}ARCHandler@{ub}  doesn't  have  full MultiUser support. But this is a
list of precautions you should take when you are installing @{b}ARCHandler@{ub} on a
MultiUser system.

Don't  set  the  u-bit  of  the @{b}ARCHandler@{ub} executable. If you would set the
u-bit  all users will be able to access all the files that the owner of the
@{b}ARCHandler@{ub} executable can access.

Use  @{"IGNOREVOLUMES" link IGNOREVOLUMES_ARG}  to  prevent @{b}ARCHandler@{ub} form using any MAssign volumes.
The  MAssign volumes that are available through @{b}ARCHandler@{ub} will reflect the
access to such a volume by the owner of the @{b}ARCHandler@{ub} task.
@endnode
@node SUPPORT "ARCHandler: Support Commands"
@prev TIPS
@next TECHNO

  @{b}@{u}Support Commands@{ub}@{uu}

The @{b}ARCHandler@{ub} archive contains several support commands:

  @{" FromARC  " link FROMARC}
  @{" ToARC    " link TOARC}

The  'Scripts'  directory of the @{b}ARCHandler@{ub} package contains similar ARexx
scripts  for  use with DiskMaster (DiskMaster by Greg Cunningham, Copyright
Progressive Periperals Inc.) and DirectoryOpus (Copyright Jonathan Potter).
@endnode
@node FROMARC "ARCHandler: FromARC"
@prev FROMARC
@next TOARC
@toc SUPPORT

  @{b}FromARC@{ub}

FromARC  is  a shell command that changes the current directory back to the
original  volume.  It  will  also  strip  all  directories from the current
directory  that  are not valid on the original volume. The command takes no
arguments.

Example:
When  the  current  directory is `Archives:Work/NewStuff/AmiCDROM-1.12.lha'
and  you  execute  the  `FromARC'  command,  the  current directory will be
changed   to  `Work:NewStuff'  (note  that  FromARC  also  strips  all  the
directories that are not valid on the original volume).

The  FromARC  and  ToARC  commands  can  only  be installed when you select
`Expert User' in the installation script.
@endnode
@node TOARC "ARCHandler: ToARC"
@prev FROMARC
@next TOARC
@toc SUPPORT

  @{b}ToARC@{ub}

ToARC is a shell command that changes the current directory of the shell to
the  same  directory on the ARC volume. The ToARC command has the following
template:

                            @{i}ToARC DEVICE/K,DIR @{ui}

The  DEVICE  argument  defaults  to  `ARC:'.  With the DIR argument you may
specify a directory/archive to enter.

Example:
When  the  current directory is `Work:NewStuff' and this directory contains
the  archive  `AmiCDROM-1.12.lha', then it's possible to enter this archive
with   the  `ToARC  AmiCDROM-1.12.lha'.  After  this  command  the  current
directory will have changed to `Archives:Work/NewStuff/AmiCDROM-1.12.lha'.

The  FromARC  and  ToARC  commands  can  only  be installed when you select
`Expert User' in the installation script.
@endnode
@node TECHNO "ARCHandler: Technical Information"
@prev WORKBENCH
@next AUTHOR

  @{b}@{u}Some technical background@{ub}@{uu}

  @{" Archive-file-lists " link FILELISTS}
  @{"    Packet types    " link PACKETS}
@endnode
@node FILELISTS "ARCHandler: Archive-file-lists"
@prev FILELISTS
@next PACKETS
@toc TECHNO

  @{b}Archive-file-lists@{ub}

When  an  archive  is  accessed for the first time @{b}ARCHandler@{ub} will scan the
contents  of  the  archive  for the files and directories that it contains.
This   list   is   kept   in   an   archive-file-list.

Several  of  these  archive-file-lists are kept in memory, even if they are
not  in  use.  The  unused  lists  are  kept  in  memory  because otherwise
@{b}ARCHandler@{ub}  would  have  to  rescan  the  archive  contents  on each access
(directory  utilities and file requesters don't keep locks on the directory
that they display).

You  can  use the @{"BUFFERS" link BUFFERS_ARG} argument or @{"Buffers" link BUFFERS_GAD} slider-gadget to specify the
number of unused lists that @{b}ARCHandler@{ub} will keep in memory.
@endnode
@node PACKETS "ARCHandler: Packet types"
@prev FILELISTS
@next PACKETS
@toc TECHNO

  @{b}Packet Types@{ub}

Currently the @{b}ARCHandler@{ub} filesystem supports the following packet types:
    ACTION_CHANGE_MODE
    ACTION_COPY_DIR
    ACTION_COPY_DIR_FH
    @{"ACTION_CREATE_DIR" link ACTION_CREATE_DIR}
    ACTION_CURRENT_VOLUME
    @{"ACTION_DELETE_OBJECT" link ACTION_DELETE_OBJECT}
    ACTION_DIE
    ACTION_DISK_INFO
    ACTION_END
    ACTION_EXAMINE_FH
    ACTION_EXAMINE_NEXT
    ACTION_EXAMINE_OBJECT
    ACTION_FH_FROM_LOCK
    ACTION_FINDINPUT
    ACTION_FINDOUTPUT°
    ACTION_FINDUPDATE°
    ACTION_FREE_LOCK
    ACTION_INFO
    ACTION_IS_FILESYSTEM
    ACTION_LOCATE_OBJECT
    ACTION_PARENT
    ACTION_PARENT_FH
    ACTION_READ
    @{"ACTION_RENAME_OBJECT" link ACTION_RENAME_OBJECT}
    ACTION_RENAME_DISK
    ACTION_SAME_LOCK
    ACTION_SEEK
    ACTION_SET_COMMENT
    ACTION_SET_DATE
    ACTION_SET_FILE_SIZE°
    ACTION_SET_OWNER°
    ACTION_SET_PROTECT
    ACTION_WRITE°

  °currently not supported in/on archive files/directories.

  
These  two  actions  don't  need  to be implemented because the dos.library
emulates  them  by using ACTION_EXAMINE_OBJECT and ACTION_EXAMINE_NEXT (and
almost nobody uses them):
    ACTION_EXAMINE_ALL
    ACTION_EXAMINE_ALL_END

Actions that may be implemented, if needed:
    ACTION_ADD_NOTIFY
    ACTION_FREE_RECORD
    ACTION_LOCK_RECORD
    ACTION_MAKE_LINK
    ACTION_READ_LINK
    ACTION_REMOVE_NOTIFY

Actions that are not supported:
    ACTION_FORMAT
    ACTION_FLUSH
    ACTION_MORE_CACHE
    ACTION_INHIBIT
    ACTION_WRITE_PROTECT

This  is  the  minimal list of packets that an underlying filesystem should
support, if you want to use it through the @{b}ARCHandler@{ub}:
    ACTION_COPY_DIR
    ACTION_END
    ACTION_EXAMINE_NEXT
    ACTION_EXAMINE_OBJECT
    ACTION_FINDINPUT
    ACTION_FREE_LOCK
    ACTION_LOCATE_OBJECT
    ACTION_PARENT
    ACTION_READ
    ACTION_SAME_LOCK
    ACTION_SEEK
@{b}ARCHandler@{ub} also uses ACTION_CHANGE_MODE for exclusive (ACCESS_WRITE) locks
on   non-archive   objects.   If   you   want  to  use  2.0  packets  (like
ACTION_COPY_DIR_FH,  ACTION_EXAMINE_FH...) the underlying filesystem should
also support these.

@{b}ARCHandler@{ub} will also try to use these packets:
    ACTION_CHANGE_MODE
    ACTION_COPY_DIR_FH
    ACTION_FH_FROM_LOCK
    ACTION_SET_FILE_SIZE
but  it  will  use  other  packets  if  the  underlying  filesystem doesn't
understand  those  packets.  Without ACTION_SET_FILE_SIZE, @{b}ARCHandler@{ub} can't
change  the  length  of  archives, especcialy when you delete files from an
archive (it will use another method to mark the end of the archive).

When  @{b}ARCHandler@{ub}  is  trying  to @{"quit" link QUITTING} but it receives a ACTION_DISK_CHANGE
before  @{b}ARCHandler@{ub}  has  been able to free all resources it will reactivate
itself. You can use this when you try to quit, but @{b}ARCHandler@{ub} isn't able to
quit  at  that  time, then you can reactivate @{b}ARCHandler@{ub} with a 'DiskChange
ARC:'.
@endnode
@node AUTHOR "ARCHandler: About the Author"
